observations.recommendation:
We recommended Management to require the: Inventory Committee to conduct and prepare report on the Physical Count of Road Network of the municipality;





Supply Officer to prepare and submit RLRN, maintain LRI, Road Map, and keep LRNPC for all roads and its components;



Municipal Engineer to provide the Supply Officer and Municipal Accountant a report on the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, with consideration to road intersections; and



Municipal Accountant to update the general ledger of the road network of the Municipality, prepare lapsing schedule for the depreciation and comply with the disclosure requirements for road network system in compliance to COA Circular No. 2015-005 dated November 23, 2015, in order to present fairly the financial statement of the agency.

We recommended that the Management require the:
Inventory Committee to conduct a comprehensive physical inventory count of all municipal roads and prepare the Report of Physical Count on Local Road Network of the Municipality;
Supply Officer to prepare and submit Report on Local Road Network, maintain Local Road Inventory, Road Map, and keep Local Road Network Property Card for all municipal roads and its components;
Municipal Engineer to provide the Supply Officer and Municipal Accountant a report on the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and
Municipal Accountant to update the general ledger of the road networks of the Municipality, derecognize the value of road networks classified as provincial and/or barangay roads, and prepare a revised lapsing schedule for the corresponding depreciation, in order to present fairly the FS of the Municipality.

We recommended Management to require the:
Inventory Committee to conduct and prepare report on the Physical Count of Road Network of the municipality;
GSO-Designate to prepare and submit RLRN, maintain LRI, Road Map, and keep LRNPC for all roads and its components;
OIC-Municipal Engineer to provide the GSO-Designate and MA a report on the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, with consideration to road intersections; and
Municipal Accountant to update the general ledger of the road network of the Municipality, prepare lapsing schedule for the depreciation and comply with the disclosure requirements for road network system in compliance to COA Circular No. 2015-005 dated November 23, 2015, in order to present fairly the financial statement of the agency.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:
a. The Local Development Council and the Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO), together with the concerned implementing offices, in coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee, immediately look into the unimplemented projects under the 20% Development Fund and determine causes of their non-implementation. Formulate/develop specific strategies/solutions to effectively implement development projects. Consider formulating a timetable within which to complete the unimplemented projects;
b. The offices concerned vigorously pursue the completion of the projects to be implemented the soonest time possible in order to achieve the objectives of the said projects in providing socio-economic benefits to the intended beneficiaries;
c. The Municipal Engineering Office improve the planning and scheduling of work activities and manpower in order to facilitate completion of the Program of Work of unimplemented projects;
d. The MPDO enhance monitoring of implementation of projects in coordination with the implementing offices and to regularly submit status reports of implementation to the Municipal Mayor for his information so that appropriate measures can be instituted to obtain optimal utilization of fund.

We recommended that Management:
a. Provide enough storage space wherein unserviceable properties could be properly secured and safeguarded against the elements and instruct all offices to surrender their reported unserviceable properties in preparation for their ultimate disposal;
b. Direct the Supply Office to finalized the Inspection and Inventory Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) as basis in recording the dropping from the books the unserviceable properties carried in the PPE accounts;
c. Direct the Appraisal and Disposal Committee to evaluate the reasonable appraisal value of the unserviceable properties listed in the IIRUP and promptly cause the sale of these properties pursuant to the directive of Section 79 of PD No. 1445, and in accordance with the procedures cited in the DBM Manual on Disposal of Government Property and COA Circular No. 89-296; and
d. Advise the concerned personnel to submit the IIRUP to the Accounting Office upon completion of the disposal activity as it will be the basis for adjusting the balances of the affected PPE accounts.

We recommended that Management:
1. Fully comply with the PDAF Decision rendered by the Supreme Court to cast away the possibility of misappropriating, and/or diverting government funds, through reversion of all remaining PDAF to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund, by depositing such to the account of the Bureau of the Treasury and;
2. Return the unutilized other trust receipts to the source agencies in accordance with COA Circular No. 94-013.

